-- 19-code-generator-proof.cell (R17, v0.2)
-- Tests: proof-carrying computation, ‚äĘ‚ąė evolution loop, ‚äĘ= crystallized
--        verifiers, oracle-gated code generation, ¬ß quotation for code-as-data,
--        guard clauses for conditional dispatch, given? for optional deps
--
-- A Cell program that takes a spec ("binary search on sorted array, returns
-- index or -1"). Generates code. Generates property tests. Runs tests (simulated).
-- If fail: analyze, rewrite, retest. If pass: generate proof sketch.
-- Oracle validates proof. Assembles proof-carrying certificate.
--
-- Demonstrates Cell's killer pattern: LLM generates (NP), verifier checks (P).
--
-- v0.2 changes from R16:
--   - ‚ä®? at file scope (v0.2 scope rules ‚ÄĒ default recovery for all cells)
--   - ‚äĘ‚ąė-managed cell oracles on generate-code are aspirational (v0.2 clarification)
--   - Guard clauses on analyze-failures, rewrite-code (conditional on fail-count)
--   - Guard clauses on proof-certificate: dispatches high/medium/low confidence
--   - ‚äĘ= expression language validated ‚ÄĒ verify-proof uses only v0.2 primitives
--     (R16 used undefined proof-covers(), missing-from(), has-loop-invariant() etc.
--      These are semantic judgments, not deterministic ‚ÄĒ moved to soft ‚ąī cell)
--   - verify-proof split: structural checks stay ‚äĘ= (crystallized), semantic
--     checks moved to verify-proof-semantic (soft cell, honest about needing LLM)
--   - ‚äĘ‚äĘ explicit accumulate/replace not needed (no spawners in this program)
--   - given? on analyze-failures for optional failure context in first pass
--   - ‚äĘ‚ąė oracles on generate-code are aspirational (loop drives improvement)

‚ä®? on failure:
  retry with ¬ęoracle.failures¬Ľ appended to prompt
  max 3 attempts

‚ä®? on exhaustion:
  partial-accept(best)

‚äĘ spec
  given description ‚Č° "binary search on sorted array, returns index or -1"
  given signature ‚Č° "binary_search(arr: int[], target: int) -> int"
  given preconditions ‚Č° "arr is sorted in ascending order, no duplicates"
  yield description, signature, preconditions

  ‚ä® description specifies the algorithm, input, and output
  ‚ä® signature has typed parameters and return type
  ‚ä® preconditions constrain the input space

‚äĘ generate-code
  given spec‚Üídescription
  given spec‚Üísignature
  given spec‚Üípreconditions
  yield ¬ßimplementation, code-text

  ‚ąī Write a correct implementation of ¬ęspec‚Üísignature¬Ľ that satisfies:
    ¬ęspec‚Üídescription¬Ľ
    Preconditions: ¬ęspec‚Üípreconditions¬Ľ

    Use a standard binary search algorithm. Return the 0-based index of
    ¬ętarget¬Ľ in ¬ęarr¬Ľ, or -1 if not found. The implementation must:
    - Use integer midpoint calculation that avoids overflow
    - Maintain loop invariant: target is in arr[lo..hi] if present
    - Terminate when lo > hi (not found) or arr[mid] == target (found)

    Output the code as a Cell ‚äĘ= expression.

  -- v0.2: aspirational under ‚äĘ‚ąė management ‚ÄĒ feedback signals, not hard gates
  ‚ä® code-text contains a loop or recursive structure
  ‚ä® code-text returns -1 for not-found case
  ‚ä® code-text uses integer division for midpoint

‚äĘ generate-property-tests
  given spec‚Üísignature
  given spec‚Üípreconditions
  given spec‚Üídescription
  yield test-cases[], properties[]

  ‚ąī Generate property-based test cases for ¬ęspec‚Üísignature¬Ľ.

    Properties to test:
    1. Found element: if target in arr, result is its index
    2. Not found: if target not in arr, result is -1
    3. Boundary: target at first position, last position
    4. Single element: array of size 1
    5. Empty array: result must be -1
    6. Midpoint correctness: target at exact midpoint

    For each property, generate 2-3 concrete test cases with
    { input-arr, input-target, expected-output }.

  ‚ä® len(test-cases) >= 10
  ‚ä® properties covers found, not-found, boundary, and edge cases
  ‚ä® each test-case has input-arr (sorted), input-target, and expected-output

‚äĘ run-tests
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  given generate-property-tests‚Üítest-cases
  yield results[], pass-count, fail-count, failure-details[]

  ‚ąī Simulate executing ¬ęgenerate-code‚Üícode-text¬Ľ on each test case
    in ¬ęgenerate-property-tests‚Üítest-cases¬Ľ. For each test:
    - Trace through the code with the given inputs
    - Record the actual output
    - Compare to expected-output
    - If mismatch: record the failure with step-by-step trace showing
      where the code diverged from expected behavior

  ‚ä® len(results) = len(generate-property-tests‚Üítest-cases)
  ‚ä® pass-count + fail-count = len(results)
  ‚ä® if fail-count > 0 then len(failure-details) = fail-count

‚äĘ analyze-failures
  given run-tests‚Üífail-count where fail-count > 0
  given run-tests‚Üífailure-details
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  yield diagnosis, bug-category, fix-strategy

  ‚ąī Analyze ¬ęrun-tests‚Üífailure-details¬Ľ against
    ¬ęgenerate-code‚Üícode-text¬Ľ. For each failure:
    - Identify the root cause (off-by-one, wrong comparison, overflow, etc.)
    - Categorize the bug
    - Propose a specific fix (which line, what change)

  ‚ä® fix-strategy describes a concrete code change
  ‚ä® bug-category ‚ąą {"off-by-one", "wrong-comparison", "overflow", "logic-error", "boundary-error"}

‚äĘ skip-analysis
  given run-tests‚Üífail-count where fail-count = 0
  yield diagnosis, bug-category, fix-strategy

  ‚äĘ= diagnosis ‚Üź "all tests pass"
  ‚äĘ= bug-category ‚Üź "none"
  ‚äĘ= fix-strategy ‚Üź "none"

‚äĘ rewrite-code
  given analyze-failures‚Üífix-strategy where fix-strategy != "none"
  given analyze-failures‚Üídiagnosis
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  given run-tests‚Üífailure-details
  yield ¬ßimplementation', code-text', changed-lines[]

  ‚ąī Apply ¬ęanalyze-failures‚Üífix-strategy¬Ľ to
    ¬ęgenerate-code‚Üícode-text¬Ľ. Rewrite only the lines that need fixing.
    Record which lines changed and why.

    The rewritten code must preserve the function signature and
    overall structure. Only fix what's broken.

  ‚ä® ¬ßimplementation' has same given/yield signature as ¬ßgenerate-code
  ‚ä® len(changed-lines) >= 1

‚äĘ skip-rewrite
  given skip-analysis‚Üífix-strategy where fix-strategy = "none"
  given generate-code‚Üícode-text
  yield ¬ßimplementation', code-text', changed-lines[]

  ‚äĘ= code-text' ‚Üź generate-code‚Üícode-text
  ‚äĘ= changed-lines ‚Üź []

  ‚ä® code-text' = generate-code‚Üícode-text

‚äĘ‚ąė evolve(generate-code, spec‚Üídescription ‚Č° spec‚Üídescription)
  through run-tests, analyze-failures, rewrite-code
  until run-tests‚Üífail-count = 0
  max 3

  -- Each iteration: generate code -> run tests -> analyze failures ->
  -- rewrite code. The rewritten code replaces generate-code's output,
  -- then tests re-run on the new version.
  --
  -- Interface frozen: generate-code always takes spec‚Üídescription and
  -- yields ¬ßimplementation + code-text. Only the implementation evolves.
  --
  -- Termination: when all tests pass (fail-count = 0) or max 3 iterations.
  --
  -- v0.2: oracles on generate-code are ASPIRATIONAL while under ‚äĘ‚ąė
  -- management ‚ÄĒ they provide feedback but do not independently block
  -- freezing. The until condition is the actual convergence gate.

‚äĘ generate-proof-sketch
  given rewrite-code‚Üícode-text'
  given generate-property-tests‚Üíproperties
  given spec‚Üípreconditions
  yield proof-sketch, invariants[], termination-argument

  ‚ąī Given the verified code ¬ęrewrite-code‚Üícode-text'¬Ľ that passes all tests,
    generate a formal proof sketch establishing correctness.

    The proof must address:
    1. **Loop invariant**: State the invariant maintained at each iteration.
       (e.g., "if target is in arr, then arr[lo] <= target <= arr[hi]")
    2. **Termination**: Prove the loop terminates.
       (e.g., "hi - lo decreases by at least 1 each iteration, bounded below by -1")
    3. **Postcondition (found)**: If arr[mid] = target, then result = mid is correct.
    4. **Postcondition (not found)**: If lo > hi, then target is not in arr[lo0..hi0].
    5. **Precondition usage**: Where does the proof rely on arr being sorted?

    Express each step as a logical proposition with justification.

  ‚ä® proof-sketch contains at least 4 logical steps
  ‚ä® invariants includes a loop invariant referencing lo, hi, and target
  ‚ä® termination-argument identifies a decreasing quantity bounded below

‚äĘ verify-proof-structural ‚Ėł crystallized
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üíproof-sketch
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üíinvariants
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üítermination-argument
  yield has-invariant, has-termination, invariant-refs-vars, step-count

  -- v0.2: ‚äĘ= uses only defined primitives (string ops, comparison, list ops)
  -- R16's verify-proof used undefined functions like proof-covers(),
  -- missing-from(), has-loop-invariant() ‚ÄĒ semantic judgments masquerading
  -- as deterministic code. Split into structural (‚äĘ=) and semantic (‚ąī).

  ‚äĘ= has-invariant ‚Üź len(invariants) >= 1
  ‚äĘ= invariant-refs-vars ‚Üź all(invariants, fn(inv) ->
    contains(inv, "lo") and contains(inv, "hi") and contains(inv, "target"))
  ‚äĘ= has-termination ‚Üź contains(termination-argument, "decrease") or
    contains(termination-argument, "decreasing") or
    contains(termination-argument, "bounded")
  ‚äĘ= step-count ‚Üź len(split(proof-sketch, "Proposition"))

  ‚ä® has-invariant = true
  ‚ä® invariant-refs-vars = true
  ‚ä® step-count >= 4

‚äĘ verify-proof-semantic
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üíproof-sketch
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üíinvariants
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üítermination-argument
  given rewrite-code‚Üícode-text'
  yield proof-valid, gaps[], verdict

  ‚ąī Evaluate the proof sketch ¬ęgenerate-proof-sketch‚Üíproof-sketch¬Ľ for
    logical completeness and correctness against the code ¬ęrewrite-code‚Üícode-text'¬Ľ.

    Check whether the proof covers:
    1. Loop invariant (references lo, hi, target; preserved by each iteration)
    2. Termination (decreasing quantity with lower bound)
    3. Found-case postcondition (arr[mid] = target implies result = mid)
    4. Not-found-case postcondition (lo > hi implies target not in arr)
    5. Precondition usage (proof relies on arr being sorted)

    Set proof-valid to true if the proof addresses all 5 points with
    sound reasoning. List any gaps (missing or incomplete arguments).

    verdict:
    - "proof complete" if proof-valid and no gaps
    - "proof valid with minor gaps" if proof-valid and 1 gap
    - "proof incomplete" if not proof-valid or 2+ gaps

  ‚ä® verdict ‚ąą {"proof complete", "proof valid with minor gaps", "proof incomplete"}
  ‚ä® if proof-valid then len(gaps) <= 1
  ‚ä® if not proof-valid then len(gaps) >= 2

‚äĘ proof-certificate-high
  given verify-proof-semantic‚Üíverdict where verdict = "proof complete"
  given verify-proof-semantic‚Üíproof-valid
  given verify-proof-semantic‚Üígaps
  given verify-proof-structural‚Üíhas-invariant
  given verify-proof-structural‚Üíhas-termination
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üíproof-sketch
  given rewrite-code‚Üícode-text'
  given run-tests‚Üípass-count
  yield certificate, confidence-level

  ‚ąī Assemble a proof-carrying certificate for ¬ęrewrite-code‚Üícode-text'¬Ľ:

    Certificate contains:
    1. The verified code
    2. The proof sketch
    3. Test results summary (all ¬ęrun-tests‚Üípass-count¬Ľ tests passing)
    4. Proof verification verdict: ¬ęverify-proof-semantic‚Üíverdict¬Ľ
    5. Structural checks: invariant present (¬ęverify-proof-structural‚Üíhas-invariant¬Ľ),
       termination argument present (¬ęverify-proof-structural‚Üíhas-termination¬Ľ)

    Confidence level: "high" ‚ÄĒ verdict is "proof complete" and all tests pass.

    This certificate is the DELIVERABLE: code + evidence of correctness.
    The LLM generated the code (NP). The crystallized verifier checked
    structural properties (P). The semantic verifier checked logical
    soundness. The tests provide empirical evidence. Together they form
    a proof-carrying computation.

  ‚äĘ= confidence-level ‚Üź "high"

  ‚ä® certificate includes code, proof, test-count, and verdict
  ‚ä® confidence-level = "high"

‚äĘ proof-certificate-medium
  given verify-proof-semantic‚Üíverdict where verdict = "proof valid with minor gaps"
  given verify-proof-semantic‚Üíproof-valid
  given verify-proof-semantic‚Üígaps
  given verify-proof-structural‚Üíhas-invariant
  given verify-proof-structural‚Üíhas-termination
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üíproof-sketch
  given rewrite-code‚Üícode-text'
  given run-tests‚Üípass-count
  yield certificate, confidence-level

  ‚ąī Assemble a proof-carrying certificate for ¬ęrewrite-code‚Üícode-text'¬Ľ.

    Certificate contains:
    1. The verified code
    2. The proof sketch
    3. Test results summary (all ¬ęrun-tests‚Üípass-count¬Ľ tests passing)
    4. Proof verification verdict: ¬ęverify-proof-semantic‚Üíverdict¬Ľ
    5. Any remaining gaps: ¬ęverify-proof-semantic‚Üígaps¬Ľ

    Confidence level: "medium" ‚ÄĒ proof is valid but has minor gaps.

  ‚äĘ= confidence-level ‚Üź "medium"

  ‚ä® certificate includes code, proof, test-count, and verdict
  ‚ä® confidence-level = "medium"

‚äĘ proof-certificate-low
  given verify-proof-semantic‚Üíverdict where verdict = "proof incomplete"
  given verify-proof-semantic‚Üíproof-valid
  given verify-proof-semantic‚Üígaps
  given generate-proof-sketch‚Üíproof-sketch
  given rewrite-code‚Üícode-text'
  given run-tests‚Üípass-count
  yield certificate, confidence-level

  ‚ąī Assemble a proof-carrying certificate for ¬ęrewrite-code‚Üícode-text'¬Ľ.
    The proof is incomplete. The certificate documents what was achieved
    and what remains to be proven.

    Certificate contains:
    1. The verified code (tests pass, but proof is lacking)
    2. The proof sketch (incomplete)
    3. Test results summary
    4. Proof verification verdict: ¬ęverify-proof-semantic‚Üíverdict¬Ľ
    5. Gaps requiring further work: ¬ęverify-proof-semantic‚Üígaps¬Ľ

    Confidence level: "low" ‚ÄĒ proof incomplete despite tests passing.

  ‚äĘ= confidence-level ‚Üź "low"

  ‚ä® certificate includes code, proof, test-count, and verdict
  ‚ä® confidence-level = "low"
